 number of contemporary movements, from Black Lives Matter and the Women’s March, to Occupy Wall Street and Standing Rock. Ultimately, this volume challenges us to re-imagine the boundaries between civil and uncivil disagreement, political reform and radical transformation, and democratic ends and means. Protest and Dissent offers thought-provoking insights into a new era of political resistance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCivil disobedience. 0aDemocracy. 0aPolitical culture. 0aProtest movements. 0aSocial movements. 7aLAW / General.2bisacsh  aActivism.  aAfrican-American Political Thought.  aAssembly.  aBlack Lives Matter.  aCitizenship.  aCivil Disobedience.  aCivil Rights Movement.  aCivil Rights.  aDemocracy.  aDemocratic Theory.  aDisobedience.  aDisorder.  aElections.  aEpistemic Injustice.  aEpistemic Violence.  aFirst Amendment.  aGene Sharp.  aIdeology.  aIncivility.  aInjustice.  aJustice.  aLabor.  aLaw and Order.  aLiberalism.  aM.K. Gandhi.  aMass Demonstrations.  aMass protest.  aNonviolence.  aNonviolent politics.  aOccupy.  aOrganizing.  aPolitical Equality.  aPolitical Legitimacy.  aPolitical Protests.  aProtests.  aRace.  aRepublicanism.  aResistance.  aResponsibility.  aSatyagraha.  aSocial Change.  aSocial Movements.  aSocial Peace.  aSolidarity.  aStrategic nonviolence.  aStrikes.  aTrump era.  aUncivil Disobedience.  aWork.1 aAkbar, Amna A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrison, Susan J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDelmas, Candice, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEl-Haj, Tabatha Abu, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHooker, Juliet, econt